There is, therefore, a decided difficulty here, not to mention thatthe transitionis intol- erably abrupt and sudden. Now the assumption of a lacuna at this junctura solves this difficulty. But il so, it also follows that the words ‘non de otiosa et quieta re loquimur’ belong to a different speaker, the very phrase itself‚ as shown in my note ad loa, point- ing to the same conclusion.

This inference will be fully justified, if we succeed in proving that the speech preceding the lacuna conflicta not only with the following utterances of Maternae, but also with those put into his mouth in c. 11-13.
